name: Personal Newsletter
description:
This Personal Newsletter Agent provides a bespoke daily digest on your favorite topics and tone. Whether you prefer industry insights, lighthearted reads, or breaking news, this agent crafts your own unique newsletter to keep you informed and entertained.


How It Works
1. Enter your favorite topics, industries, or areas of interest.
2. Choose your tone—professional, casual, or humorous.
3. Set your preferred delivery cadence: daily or weekly.
4. The agent scans top sources and compiles 3–5 engaging stories, insights, and fun facts into a conversational newsletter.

Skip the morning scroll and enjoy a thoughtfully curated newsletter designed just for you. Stay ahead of trends, spark creative ideas, and enjoy an effortless, informed start to your day.


Use Cases
• Executives: Get a daily digest of market updates and leadership insights.
• Marketers: Receive curated creative trends and campaign inspiration.
• Entrepreneurs: Stay updated on your industry without information overload.
instructions:
1. Enter your topic and email address.
2. Connect the Gmail inbox you want to send from. (I just have mine send to myself.)
3. Choose the time period you want the email to cover — for example, “3 days.”
4. Set the agent’s schedule to match that time period. If you want a newsletter every 3 days, set it to run every 3 days.

Once you’ve got your first schedule set up, you can add more!
For example, I have three newsletter schedules running — each on a different topic — that land in my inbox on different days.

input_default.description: How would you like the newsletter to be written?

input_default.prompt:
You are a skilled newsletter writer for a popular newsletter, which covers the topic: "{{topic | safe}}" 
Today's date is "{{today | safe}}"
Your newsletter gets sent out on the following repeat rate: "{{recency | safe}}"

Create a newsletter using the provided research in the following writing style: {{style | safe}}

Follow the Morning Coffee style: conversational tone, clever headlines, and a mix of serious insights with light-hearted comments. 

Include 3-5 main stories and 2-3 shorter snippets or fun facts. Use emojis sparingly for emphasis. End with a thought-provoking question if appropriate.
Include dates for every story (only based on the research below, never assume dates, if not present just omit the date). You don't need to write a formal date, you can say things like "On Monday" or "Yesterday" when accurate and to do so.

Here is the research for today's letter:
<research>
{{research | safe}}
</research>

Do not cover stories not present in the research or make any assumptions. Base your newsletter on this research.

Output this edition of the newsletter in the following format: 

<title>
The title of this edition of the newsletter
</title>

<body>
The content of this edition of the newsletter to be sent out to it's readers (formatted in markdown, no additional commentary, will be auto-sent as-is
</body>

inputs.Report Design Brief:
## ✳️ Design Brief — “Human-Crafted Simplicity” ### 🎯 **Goal** Create an HTML email that feels **designed by hand**, not generated by a template. The visual tone should be **calm, confident, and editorial**, with natural rhythm and whitespace. The layout should read easily on desktop and mobile, maintaining a **friendly, premium newsletter** vibe. --- ### 🧱 **Layout Structure** * **Width:** 600px fixed, centered (`align="center"`) * **Padding:** 24–32px inner margin on all sides * **Grid:** Single-column layout (no sidebars or multiple columns) * **Flow:** 1. Header area (title or logo text) 2. Intro paragraph (optional) 3. Content sections stacked vertically 4. Optional footer / signature Each section should feel like a “block” of thought — separated by whitespace, not borders. --- ### 🎨 **Color Palette** * **Background:** Off-white / warm neutral (`#fffaf2`, `#fffefc`, or `#fdfbf7`) * **Text:** Soft black (`#1a1a1a`) * **Secondary Text:** Muted gray (`#666`) * **Accent Color:** One strong, warm tone (e.g. amber `#f5b200` or coral `#ff6b4a`) * **Highlight Backgrounds:** Light tint of accent (`#fff4e0` or `#fff2e2`) * **Links:** Accent color or slightly darker version Overall, aim for **soft contrast** — no harsh blacks or bright whites. --- ### 🗚 **Typography** * **Font Family:** `Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif` (system fonts preferred for email) * **Base Size:** 16px * **Line Height:** 1.6–1.8 * **Hierarchy:** * **Main Title:** 28–32px, bold, tight spacing, strong top margin * **Section Titles:** 20–22px, semibold, margin-bottom 12px * **Body Text:** 16px, normal weight * **Meta Text / Footnotes:** 14px, gray (#777) * **Letter Spacing:** Slight positive spacing (0.1–0.2px) for a polished feel Avoid underlines; instead, use color and weight for emphasis. --- ### ⚪ **Spacing and Rhythm** * **Vertical rhythm** is everything: * 48px between major sections * 24px between heading and paragraph * 8–12px between lines or inline elements * Avoid even repetition — vary spacing subtly between elements to feel more human. * Never use visible borders to divide; use padding and whitespace. --- ### 🧩 **Visual Elements** * Use **colored spans** or **highlight backgrounds** to create visual variety: ```html highlight text ``` * Soft rounded corners on any background block (6–8px radius). * Occasional use of horizontal rules (`
`) allowed only if light gray (`#eee`) and with generous vertical spacing. * Features images clearly grouped with their relevant text, small caption text below the image where available. --- ### 🧭 **Sections** Each section should feel distinct through typography and whitespace, not hard dividers. Example section pattern: * Title → body → small callout or quote * Use **a single accent element** per section (highlighted text, tinted background block, or colored link). * No boxes around “Why it matters”–style callouts; instead, lightly tinted background or italicized text block. --- ### 📱 **Responsiveness** * Ensure readability on mobile: * Maintain 16px font minimum * Auto-scale images and block widths * Increase line spacing slightly on mobile (`line-height: 1.8`) --- ### 🧾 **Footer** * Simple and unintrusive. * Muted gray text, small font size (14px). * Optional subtle top border (`#eee`) or generous top margin (40–48px). --- ### 💡 **Design Keywords** > Warm • Minimal • Human • Editorial • Spacious • Typographically-driven • Confident • Soft

input_default.prompt:
Extract and list the individual stories mentioned in the following newsletter which you believe would benefit from an accompanying picture.
When making this decision, consider which stories are likely to have the best pictures available online. Do not just select every story. Consider how many images would be appropriate for a newsletter.
For each story you choose, output a clear, descriptive title that would make sense as a search query — not necessarily the original headline.  

Output the results in XML format as follows:

<stories>
  <story>Man lands on the moon</story>
  <story>NASA announces next Mars mission</story>
</stories>

Here is the newsletter content:
<newsletter>
{{newsletter | safe}}
</newsletter>

You are given a newsletter. Each story includes an associated image URL. While not every image needs to be used (as too many may overcrowd the layout), it might also make sense to include them all—use your judgment.

Your task is to reproduce the newsletter **verbatim** in markdown format, inserting the image URLs where they fit best. 

Do not alter or reword the newsletter text in any way—this is absolutely critical. Simply return the unedited newsletter text with the image URLs appropriately placed. Include no extra commentary, explanation, or decoration—only the final markdown output.


Here is the newsletter and the URLs:

<newsletter>
{{newsletter | safe}}
</newsletter>

<image_urls>
{{image_urls | safe}}
</image_urls>

Now, respond with the final newsletter text with no additional commentary, explanation, or decoration.

sub_graphs.name: Image Search
sub_graphs.description: Search the web for images, get back image urls.

input_default.prompt:
Extract the most relevant image URL(s) that represent the following query from the text below. 
Do not return more than {{max_results}} images under any circumstances.

<query>
{{query | safe}}
</query>

<raw_text>
{{results | safe}}
</raw_text>

Respond using the following XML structure:
- Wrap all images in a single <images> tag (even if there is only one image).
- For each image, include:
  - The full image URL inside <url> ... </url>
  - A short image description inside <image_description> ... </image_description>
- Wrap each image’s data in an <image> ... </image> block.

Example:
<images>
  <image>
    <url>https://example.com/image1.png</url>
    <image_description>The image depicts a sunrise over the mountains.</image_description>
  </image>
  <image>
    <url>https://example.com/image2.jpg</url>
    <image_description>A close-up of a person hiking on a rocky trail.</image_description>
  </image>
</images>

Try to return up to {{max_results}} relevant images, but exclude any that are not relevant.
